   "source": [
    "# 📐 2026 MEASUREMENT SCIENCE FRAMEWORK\n",
    "\n",
    "> *\"The goal of 2026 evaluation is metrological traceability: the ability to relate any given AI performance measurement to national or international standards through an unbroken chain of comparisons.\"*  \n",
    "> — **NIST AI 800-3, Expanding the AI Evaluation Toolbox with Statistical Models, 2026**\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## How **ARTIFEX v7.2 Spanish Benchmark** Fits the 2026 Evaluation Paradigm\n",
    "\n",
    "**ARTIFEX v7.2** evaluates safety models on a 68-prompt Colombian-context Spanish benchmark. This notebook directly operationalizes **external validity** testing:\n\n- **Locale variation** (es-CO vs. es-ES vs. es-MX) exposes construct drift\n- **X-Value Radar charts** visualize coverage across cultural value dimensions\n- **Consensus vs. Pluralism taxonomy** distinguishes universal from culturally relative harms\n\nIn IRT terms, each benchmark prompt is an *item* with a `difficulty` parameter $b_i$ and `discrimination` parameter $a_i$. The Colombian context shifts the item parameter distribution relative to Western-centric training data — a form of **DIF (Differential Item Functioning)** analysis critical to equitable safety evaluation.\n\n> *\"Non-exhaustive image labeling and class hierarchies — features of Open Images-style evaluation — are directly analogous to the cultural incompleteness problem in multilingual safety.\"*\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Five Facets of Validity — ARTIFEX Alignment\n",
    "\n",
    "| Validity Facet | Description | ARTIFEX Implementation |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Content** | Does the benchmark cover the full construct domain? | `cultural_taxonomy.yaml` + BCP-47 language coverage |\n",
    "| **Construct** | Does the measure align with theoretical expectations? | Dual-encoder embeddings + BERTopic cluster coherence |\n",
    "| **Criterion** | Does the score predict real-world outcomes? | Bias-corrected θ̂ (Zheng et al. arXiv:2503.23339) |\n",
    "| **External** | Does the result generalize across settings? | Cross-lingual & cross-dialect evaluation |\n",
    "| **Consequential** | What are the impacts of using this evaluation? | BBOM Layer 9 compliance + auditability log |\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### IRT 3PL Item Response Model\n",
    "\n",
    "ARTIFEX evaluation items are analyzed through the lens of **Item Response Theory (IRT)**. The probability of a correct safety verdict on item $i$ by a model with latent ability $\\\\theta$ is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P_i(\\\\theta) = c_i + \\\\frac{1 - c_i}{1 + e^{-a_i(\\\\theta - b_i)}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "- $a_i$ = **discrimination** — how well item $i$ distinguishes between model ability levels\n",
    "- $b_i$ = **difficulty** — the ability level at which $P_i(\\\\theta) = 0.5 + c_i/2$  \n",
    "- $c_i$ = **pseudo-guessing** — probability of correct verdict by chance\n",
    "\n",
    "*Items with **negative discrimination** ($a_i < 0$) indicate annotation errors or construct mismatch — a BBOM Layer 9 failure gate.*\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### NIST GLMM Framework — Variance Decomposition\n",
    "\n",
    "Per **NIST AI 800-3**, generalized linear mixed models (GLMMs) decompose evaluation variance into:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Total Variance = Between-Item Variance (difficulty)\n",
    "               + Within-Item Variance  (model inconsistency)\n",
    "               + Residual              (noise)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "FiftyOne's per-sample metrics + ARTIFEX's jury routing directly implement this decomposition.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**References:** NIST AI 800-3 (2026) · ISO/IEC 42119-2/3 · arXiv:2603.00063 · arXiv:2511.04689 · arXiv:2602.00521\n"
   ]
